Section 1: Let's Dive In!

Our simple first app

Source: https://codesandbox.io/s/react-jg4cq


Aim: Translate Input into Output using preferred language at the bottom.

The App() function in App.js and the definition of a React component



The App() function is a React component, which is a plain JavaScript function that returns some JSX.

A React component has two jobs:

  • Produces a JSX: which tells React what component to display on the screen.
  • Handles UserEvent: For example, when user types some text input, or clicking on a button.


JSX


  • What is JSX


    JSX is a set of instructions to tell React exactly what content to display on the screen at any given time. JSX syntax is very similar to HTML and follows many similar rules. JSX is technically a special dialect of JS. It is not understandable by our web browsers.

    JSX is processed by the Babel. The Babel converts JSX into equivalent HTML.

    When we use React, we don't have to use JSX however it is highly recommender as JSX is much easier to read.

    The differences between JSX and HTML can be found here, where we look into building HTML content using JSX.

  • How React uses JSX

    React JSX element can be used to create a normal HTML element, or to show another element.

    For every JSX, React will loop through the elements within. When React looks at a JSX element, it will ask itself whether that element is a standard DOM element.

    If Yes, it will display that element on the HTML.

    If No, it will check whether it is a component. If Yes, it will call the component function and inspect all the JSX that it gets back.

    Example: Let's look at this line in the return() statement of App():

    return (
  <div>
    <Field label="Enter English" onChange={setText} value={text} />
              ...
);

    React will ask itself: "Is <div> a standard DOM element?" - Yes. Then it will move on to <Field..> and the answer is No, this is not a standard DOM vanilla element, however it is a component that was created and imported with:

    import Field from "./components/field";

    What React will do is look at the ./components/field.js file and iterate through the default() function:

    import React from "react";

export default ({ label, value, onChange }) => {
  return (
    <div>
      <label>{label}</label>
      <input
        className="input"
        value={value}
        onChange={e => onChange(e.target.value)}
      />
    </div>
  );
};
    • Is <div> a DOM element? Yes -> Display that on the screen.
    • Is <label> a DOM element? Yes -> Display that on the screen.
    • Is <input> a DOM element? Yes -> Display that on the screen.

    Then, React will go back to App.js and move on to the <Languages> element. It does this repeatedly until it has walked over all components.

The index.js file


In the public directory, we can see the index.html file that is loaded up on the browser. Then the request is going to go back to our folder and look for additional javascript files. The first file that gets requested and boots up our whole React application is the index.js file which is:

import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom";
import App from "./App";

ReactDOM.render(<App />, document.getElementById("root"));

The important line is:

ReactDOM.render(<App />, document.getElementById("root"));

In the render() call. we have a few arguments:

  • <App /> tells React to call the App function and get back the JSX output, then turn it into HTML.
  • document.getElementbyId("root") tells React where to display the App function within the HTML.

index.js: The imported libraries


In index.js we imported two libraries: React and ReactDOM, what are they? It turns out that when we refer to and use React, we actually interact with two seperate libraries.

The React library itself knows how to work with components. It can be referred to as a reconciler.

The ReactDOM knows how to take instructions on what we want to show, and display that by turning it into HTML. It can be referred to as the renderer.

The useState() functions

In the App.js file, what are these?

export default function App() {
  const [language, setLanguage] = useState("ru");
  const [text, setText] = useState("");

The useState() functions are used to work with the React 'state' system, which is all about managing data in our application that changes over time.

In our application, both the language and the text element are changed over time.

State is used to keep track of data that changes over time. It is also used by React to update the HTML on the screen.

Session 2: Building Contents with JSX

Our first local app

General

In the previous example, we used Codepen. It is great however it is not used for professional projects.

So, we'll generate a new local React project. We need to start out a few things..

sudo pacman -S nodejs npm
sudo npm install -g create-react-app

Then we can create a React app:

create-react-app jsx

This will create a folder jsx in our current directory with a lot of files.

Why do we use create-react-app? It generates a React project that comes with a ton of dependencies that are set up behind the scenes so we don't have to do anything. Some of the core dependencies include:

  • Babel : A command-line tool that can take codes of any version of JavaScript and outputs a newer version of it.


Babel also converts JSX to HTML. It is much easier to write our JSX elements using React, which are translated into JavaScript code to create HTML elements by the Babel, than to write them using just JavaScript. As we can see below, the converted Javascript version of a simple JSX format is much more difficult to read.


We can play around with the Babel on https://babeljs.io/:


  • Webpack
  • Dev Server

Exploring a Create-React-App project

On creation, a Create-React-App Project looks like this:

.
├── .git
├── .gitignore
├── node_modules
├── package.json
├── package-lock.json
├── public
├── README.md
└── src

4 directories, 4 files
  • src: Where all of our codes are stored. To learn React app, we can delete all the automatically generated files and create our own.
  • public: HTML files or any files that are served to our users.
  • node_modules contain all the dependencies that we need to have our app up and running. We'll likely never have to go into this.
  • package.json is used to record project dependencies.
  • package-lock.json records exact version of project dependencies.
  • README.md contains the general instructions.

.. and of course the generic git directories.

Starting and Storing the app

cd jsx
npm start


As we are learning React app, we will delete all the files in src folder.

index.js

Then, we'll create index.js. This is a special file so we have to make sure that the name has to be correct.

Within the index.js file, we will be performing three tasks:

// Import the React and React Dom libraries
import React from 'react'
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom';

// Create a React component
const App = function() {
    return <div>Hello there!</div>;
}

// Take the React component and display on screen
ReactDOM.render(
    <App />,
    document.querySelector('#root')
);

Note:

  • Step 1: Import: The import statement is structure like import something from "module-name"; where "something" is the name of the variable that will refer to the default export from the module "module-name", which should be in the node_modules folder. This is a variable that we'll be using ourselves to refer to, so instead of import React... we could use anything like import batman.. and it will still work.


The import statement is similar to the require function of the CommonJS Modules. The import statement is used in reference to the module system ES2015. CommonJS Modules is another one of module system.

  • Step 2: Create a React Component: In the above example, we have created a function-based React Component. Instead of using function(), we could also have used the arrow-based function syntax which is () =>. This React function will be converted to a Javascript function by the Babel:


  • Step 3: Show the React component on the screen by putting it into a JSX: We will be taking the App() React component, that was created in step 2 and put it into a self-closing JSX tag: <App />. The second element refers to the existing DOM element root that already exists inside our html file.

The HTML file in this case is the index.html inside our project public folder.

Our page, will look like this:


Difference between JSX and HTML

  • Three main differences

    In general, JSX and HTML are very similar and any existing knowledge that we have about HTML will be applicable for JSX. There are however three main differences, these can be found when:

    • Adding custom styling to an element
    • Adding a class to an element
    • JSX can reference JS variables

    We'll look at the differences between HTML and JSX by playing around.

    First, we'll start with using plain HTML in our React component:

    // Import the React and React Dom libraries
import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom";

// Create a React component
const App = function () {
  return (
    <div>
      <label class="label" for="name">
        Enter name:
      </label>
      <input id="name" type="text" />
      <button style="background-color: blue; color: white">Submit</button>
    </div>
  );
};

// Take the React component and display on screen
ReactDOM.render(<App />, document.querySelector("#root"));

    Note:

    • What the for="name" bit does in the <label> element is that if we click on the 'Enter name' inner HTML, the input will be selected.
    • The JSX bit on the return statement, which is written in plain HTML is wrapped inside a pair of brackets so that they can span multiple lines.

    When we look at the our page using a browser, we'll see some error messages:

    Error: The `style` prop expects a mapping from style properties to values, not a string. For example, style={{marginRight: spacing + 'em'}} when using JSX.
    in button (at src/index.js:13)
    in div (at src/index.js:8)
    in App (at src/index.js:19)


    This error is thrown because adding custom styling to an element requires different syntaxes for HTML and JSX.

    For custom styling, in JSX, we need to change the syntax a bit.

    • After the = we need to start with two pair of curly braces. The outer curly braces indicate that we want to reference a JavaScript variable inside of our JSX. The inner curly braces indicates that we want to use a JavaScript object. The key of this JavaScript object indicates the values that we want to use for styling.
    • Anytime we need to use - in JSX for compound style property in custom styling, instead we'd use camel case.

    Therefore, we'll need to our code to:


    and our page would be generated.

    Then, we'll look at the difference between JSX and HTML for adding a class to an element. When we use JSX, our syntax needs to be a bit different. Instead of using class, use className, like so:

    INSTEAD OF:

    <label class="label" for="name">

    USE:

    <label className="label" for="name">

    Why? This is because the keyword class is used already in Javascript. Therefore we want to use className in JSX to avoid keyword clash. This used to be a problem, however these days Babel should be smart enough to distinguish between the differences. Therefore, this requirement is a bit more relaxed.

    Lastly, JSX can very easily reference Javascript variable. This is actually one of the most important feature of JSX.

    Quick example: we'll reference a JS variable inside our JSX for the button label:

    // Import the React and React Dom libraries
import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom";

// Create a React component
const App = function () {
  const buttonText = "Click Me";

  return (
    <div>
      <label className="label" for="name">
        Enter name:
      </label>
      <input id="name" type="text" />
      <button style={{ backgroundColor: "blue", color: "white" }}>
        {buttonText}
      </button>
    </div>
  );
};

// Take the React component and display on screen
ReactDOM.render(<App />, document.querySelector("#root"));


    Instead of referencing just a const, this feature can potentially be used for more complicated, like referencing a function!

    // Import the React and React Dom libraries
import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom";

function getButtonText() {
    return 'Click on Me';
}

// Create a React component
const App = function () {
  const buttonText = "Click Me";

  return (
    <div>
      <label className="label" for="name">
        Enter name:
      </label>
      <input id="name" type="text" />
      <button style={{ backgroundColor: "blue", color: "white" }}>
        { getButtonText() }
      </button>
    </div>
  );
};

// Take the React component and display on screen
ReactDOM.render(<App />, document.querySelector("#root"));


  • JSX - reference Javascript variables


    There are however only a few types of values that we can reference in JSX.

    • String
    • Integer
    • Array of string and/or integer

    Something that will lead to bug very frequently. Suppose we want to be fancy and do this:

    We'll run into this error:

    Error: Objects are not valid as a React child (found: object with keys {text}). If you meant to render a collection of children, use an array instead.
    in button (at src/index.js:15)

    The error means that we are trying to show a Javascript object inside of a React component, as text and React does not know how to deal with that.

    We can fix that by changing { button } to { button.text } to refer to the text element of the button element.

    This feature is related to how we can add custom styling to JSX, where we have to use two pairs of curly braces with the outer pair to wrap the variable and the inner pairs to wrap the Javascript object.

  • Other small differences between JSX and HTML

    There are other minor differences between JSX and HTML. We need to know how to spot them.

    If we keep using the same code from the above example, and open our browser Console, we'll see this warning message:

    index.js:1 Warning: Invalid DOM property `for`. Did you mean `htmlFor`?
    in label (at src/index.js:12)
    in div (at src/index.js:11)
    in App (at src/index.js:24)

    This is a small difference. To fix it we just need to follow the suggestion and change for to htmlFor. It's not really an issue however similarly to the class and className thing, Javascript wants to avoid keyword clash.

    As these are smaller things, we'll still be able to display our page. However it is good practice to always have the console open so that we can address these warnings.

  • When to use double quotes and when to use single quotes

    In JSX, use " anytime we want to indicate a string.

    For any non-JSX property, use '. We can also use double-quotes for these, however single-quote is the community convention.

Session 3: Communicating with Props

In this section, we'll build a simple app that looks like a simple comment section. We'll first take a naive approach by hardcoding all individual comment elements by copy-pasting, then we'll refactor our code.


create-react-app components

The three Tenets of React Components


  • Component Nesting is the concept of nesting components within each other to make a usable React application.
  • Component Reusability is the concept of writing components so that the codes can be reused within our application. DRY.
  • Component Configuration: our reusable component should also be re-configurable.

Semantic UI CDN

Semantic UI is an open-source CSS framework that can be used for styling. We'll be using this library.

For our project, we'll be using this: https://semantic-ui.com/views/comment.html

Instead of installing all the Semantic UI packages, we can instead look up "Semantic UI CDN" and go to here: https://cdnjs.com/libraries/semantic-ui. On this site we can see all the public-hosted Semantic UI CSS files so that we can use it inside of our project. We'll be using this one: https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/semantic-ui/2.4.1/semantic.min.css.

We'll add it inside the <head> tag inside our public/index.html file

npm install --save faker

Refactoring React & Create a reusable and configurable component

General approach

In order to effectively create a reusable and configurable component, we need to take a few steps:

  • Identify the JSX that appears to be duplicated.
  • What is the purpose of that JSX block? Think of a descriptive name for what it does. This is one of the most important of our component.
  • Create a new file for this new component. It should have the same name as the the component.
  • Create a new component in the new file, paste the JSX into it.
  • Make the new component configurable using React's 'props' system.

In action

The duplicated component in our project is the comment. We'll name it CommentDetail.

We'll then create a CommentDetail.js inside our src/ directory.

For the naming of React component as well as the actual class, in Javascript the common naming method is to use uppercase, or proper form.

Then, the next step is to simply copy and paste the JSX component into this file:

Then, we need to export the CommentDetail component to make it available to other files within our project. Then, it will need to be imported into our index.js file. What we are doing is like so:

The exporting is done by a single line at the end of CommentDetail.js:

export default CommentDetail;

.. and the importing is done in index.js by:

import CommentDetail from './CommentDetail';

Once we have imported CommentDetail into our index.js, we will use it through the technique known as Component Nesting.

import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom';
import CommentDetail from './CommentDetail';

const App = () => {
    return (
      <div className="ui container comments">
          <CommentDetail />
      </div>
    );
};

ReactDOM.render(
    <App />,
    document.querySelector('#root')
);

Why didn we use <CommentDetail /> but not {CommentDetail()} ? Remember that in order to reference Javascript variable inside a JSX, we need to put it in a pair of curly braces. React Component is the single exception to this rule. We can treat a component like a JSX tag instead.

This code should work to display one single Comment. The actual CommentDetail object also still has hard-coded author and metadata. This is when we start to look at the props system in React, which can be used to make our component configurable.

Using React Props system to make component configurable


In React, the Props, short for Properties, system is used to pass data from a parent component to a child *(nested) component. The entire goal of this system is to enable communicating data from the parent component to the child component so that the child component is customizable and configurable.

In our current project, the goal is to implement a system where the parent App component can pass a little bit of data to the child CommentDetail componenet while calling it to supposedly tell the CommentDetail how to display the author name.


When we use the Props system, there are two stages that we need to go through

  • The first stage in which we want to provide data from Parent to Child.
  • The second stage in which the Child consumes data from the Parent.

It will look like so:

(The syntax looks similar to the syntax that is used to add attribute to a JSX element.)

To implement this in our project, let's first provide the props to the child CommentDetail component within the parent component App:

Secondly, we need to make sure that the Child component can consume this data. This is done inside of CommentDetail.js.

So far, the way we have defined our CommentDetail component is by using:

const CommentDetail = (props) => {

In practice, we want to reference the props by something like the below. Then, we'll also log the props to console, so we can see how it looks like.

const CommentDetail = props => {
  console.log(props);
  return (...


As we can see, the props object is a Javascript with a key-value pair inside of it. The key we can see is the author key which we referenced in the index.js file in the parent App component.

So now, in order to reference the author data passed from the Parent component, we simply need to do:

We can also pass multiple props to a child component. It's simply an extension from what we just did.

index.js

import React from "react";
import ReactDOM from "react-dom";
import CommentDetail from "./CommentDetail";
import faker from "faker";

const App = () => {
  return (
    <div className="ui container comments">
      <CommentDetail
        author="Sam"
        timeAgo="Today at 4:45PM"
        content="Great post!"
        avatar={faker.image.avatar()}
      />
      <CommentDetail
        author="Alex"
        timeAgo="Today at 6:30PM"
        content="Super Helpful!"
        avatar={faker.image.avatar()}
      />
      <CommentDetail
        author="David"
        timeAgo="Yesterday at 5:00PM"
        content="Please contact me via abc@xyz.com"
        avatar={faker.image.avatar()}
      />
    </div>
  );
};

ReactDOM.render(<App />, document.querySelector("#root"));

CommentDetail.js

import React from "react";

const CommentDetail = props => {
  return (
    <div className="comment">
      <a href="/" className="avatar">
        <img alt="avatar" src={props.avatar} />
      </a>
      <div className="content">
        <a href="/" className="author">
          {props.author}
        </a>
        <div className="metadata">
          <span className="date">{props.timeAgo}</span>
        </div>
        <div className="text">{props.content}</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};

export default CommentDetail;

  • Always have the Browser Console open to address warnings/ error messages.
